 doubt about which branch<br />&gt; it was if there's a problem.<br /><br />Yeah, I'm definitely ok with octopus merges, and I do them myself<br />occasionally (especially with the -tip tree, which I get as many<br />separate pull requests - see for example commit 669fc2f0c70a).<br /><br />And various maintainers use them too - Ingo does them for x86, Russell<br />King does them for ARM, Roland Dreier for infiniband, Paul McKenney<br />for rcu stuff, etc etc. Len Brown used to do them for ACPI all the<br />time.<br /><br />But I do ask people to use them judiciously. Octopus merges are good<br />for the "many small topic branches" kind of thing. But they should<br />generally be avoided for big merges.<br /><br />Obligatory git trick of the day:<br /><br />    git rev-list --parents HEAD |<br />        egrep '^.{128}' |<br />        cut -d' ' -f1 |<br />        git log --no-walk --stdin --oneline<br /><br />shows you the octopus merges. A couple of the older ones are bogus and<br />come from the bad old days when git didn't properly filter parent<br />lists, so there are redundant parents making a commit _look_ like an<br />octopus merge even though it's really just merging one branch. Maybe<br />Takashi hit one of those bugs back when..<br /><br />                      Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
